  "description": [
    "Our Stake In Foreign Affairs 6 N The CIO NEWS December 18 1944 In calling to the attention of the Senate the position of the Congress of Industrial Or ganizations on foreign policy Pres Philip Mur ray has urged the most careful consideration of every appointee and policy concerned with international affairs His advice applies not only to our repre sentatives in Washington but also to the peo ple who elected them For it is certainly the peoples business to see that a peoples peace results from this peoples war The future lives livelihood and freedom of all of us depend to day more than ever before on what Is usually called foreign policy Every CIO member in particular should study the ClOs unanimously adopted policy and be alert to see that its patriotic and pro gressive principles are adhered to by his re presentatives The first point in ClOs foreign policy Is United Nations unity for the complete de struction of Axis tyranny and for postwar reconstruction and full support for Presi dent Roosevelts determined leadership in this direction ClOs next point is that there must be no negotiated or soft peace This reflects la bors determination that there"
